Great question — parallel streams are powerful but have several traps that can cause bugs, poor performance, or even data corruption. Here's what you must keep in mind:

---

## 🔒 1. Thread Safety (Most Critical)
- **Never use non-thread-safe objects shared across threads** — e.g., `XPath`, `DocumentBuilder`, `SimpleDateFormat`
- Use `ThreadLocal` to give each thread its own instance (as done in our code)
- Avoid shared mutable state — don't update a shared variable inside a parallel stream

```java
// ❌ WRONG — race condition
int count = 0;
records.parallelStream().forEach(r -> count++); // not atomic!

// ✅ CORRECT
long count = records.parallelStream().filter(...).count();
```

---

## 📦 2. Collector Must Be Thread-Safe
- `Collectors.toMap()` throws `ConcurrentModificationException` in parallel
- Always use `Collectors.toConcurrentMap()` for parallel streams

```java
// ❌ WRONG
.collect(Collectors.toMap(...))

// ✅ CORRECT
.collect(Collectors.toConcurrentMap(...))
```

---

## ⚠️ 3. Duplicate Keys in the Map
- If two records have the same `id`, `toConcurrentMap()` will throw `IllegalStateException`
- Always provide a **merge function** as the 3rd argument to handle duplicates

```java
Collectors.toConcurrentMap(
    Record::getId,
    record -> pathExists(record.getXmlString(), xpathExpression),
    (existing, newVal) -> existing  // keep first, or apply your logic
)
```

---

## 💥 4. Exception Handling Inside Streams
- Streams don't play well with checked exceptions — they silently swallow or crash
- Wrap risky logic in a helper method with try/catch and return a safe default

```java
// ❌ WRONG — checked exception crashes the stream
.map(r -> riskyMethod(r))  // won't compile if it throws checked exception

// ✅ CORRECT — handle inside helper
private static boolean pathExists(String xml, String path) {
    try { ... }
    catch (XPathExpressionException e) { return false; }
}
```

---

## 🐌 5. Parallel Doesn't Always Mean Faster
Parallel streams use the **common ForkJoinPool** (shared across your whole JVM). Bad cases:

| Scenario | Use Parallel? |
|---|---|
| 100k+ CPU-heavy records | ✅ Yes |
| Small lists (< 1000 items) | ❌ No, overhead wins |
| I/O bound work (DB, network) | ❌ No, threads block |
| Simple map/filter ops | ❌ Sequential is faster |

For I/O-bound work, use a custom `ExecutorService` instead.

---

## 🔢 6. Order Is Not Guaranteed
- `parallelStream()` does **not** preserve encounter order by default
- If order matters (e.g., ordered output, logging sequence), use `.forEachOrdered()` or sort after

```java
// ❌ order not guaranteed
records.parallelStream().forEach(System.out::println);

// ✅ if order matters
records.parallelStream().forEachOrdered(System.out::println);
```
Note: `.forEachOrdered()` reduces parallelism benefit — prefer collecting to a map instead.

---

## 🧵 7. ForkJoinPool Starvation
- All parallel streams share the **same common pool** by default
- If one task blocks (e.g., I/O, sleep), it starves other parallel tasks in your app
- For heavy workloads, use a **dedicated pool**:

```java
ForkJoinPool customPool = new ForkJoinPool(8); // control thread count
Map<String, Boolean> result = customPool.submit(() ->
    records.parallelStream()
        .collect(Collectors.toConcurrentMap(
            Record::getId,
            r -> pathExists(r.getXmlString(), xpathExpression),
            (a, b) -> a
        ))
).get();
customPool.shutdown();
```

---

## 🗂️ 8. Input List Type Matters
- `ArrayList` splits well for parallel — good performance ✅
- `LinkedList` splits poorly — parallel gives no benefit ❌
- If your source is a `LinkedList` or stream from DB, convert first:

```java
List<Record> records = new ArrayList<>(dbResultList); // ensure good splitting
```

---

## 🧹 9. ThreadLocal Cleanup (Memory Leaks)
- `ThreadLocal` values live as long as the thread lives
- In thread pools (like ForkJoinPool), threads are reused — stale values can linger
- Clean up after if needed:

```java
XPATH_THREAD_LOCAL.remove(); // call after processing is done
```

---

## ✅ Quick Checklist Before Writing Parallel Stream Code

- [ ] Are all shared objects thread-safe or `ThreadLocal`?
- [ ] Using `toConcurrentMap()` not `toMap()`?
- [ ] Handled duplicate keys with a merge function?
- [ ] All exceptions caught inside helper methods?
- [ ] Data size large enough to justify parallelism?
- [ ] Source collection is `ArrayList` (splits well)?
- [ ] Order doesn't matter, or handled explicitly?
- [ ] Not doing I/O inside the stream?
- [ ] Consider custom `ForkJoinPool` if sharing is a concern?
